function varargout = getRefractiveIndex(material, lambda, varargin)
%% Code to get the refractive index and the Sellmeier equations for quite
% a few  materials (mostly interesting for mid-infrared applications) +
% related information about them (dispersion parameters, bandgap,
% nonlinear refractive index for example)
%
% Version 1.14
%
% List of materials : air, Ar, As2S3, BBO, BK7, CaCO3, CaF2, CdTe, DKDP,
%                       UVFS, GaSe, Ge, He, HgS, KDP, KRS5, KBr, Kr, LBO,
%                       LiF, MgF2, MgOCLN, NaCl, N, Ne, Sapphire, SF10,
%                       SF11, Si, Suprasil, Xe, YAG, ZnS, ZnSe, ZnTe
%
% Input parameters : - material : string with the name of the material. The
%                       only materials in the database are the one cited
%                       above
%                    - lambda : Wavelength at which you want to know the
%                       data about the material (in meters). This can also
%                       be an array of wavelength and in that case, the
%                       output will be an array with the corresponding
%                       refractive indices
%                    - additional parameters (optional) :
%                       - axis (relevant only for birefringent materials).
%                           In case of non birefringent material, enter x.
%                           In case of uniaxial or biaxial crystal, n_x,
%                           n_y and n_z are sorted as n_x < n_y < n_z. You
%                           can either use x, y and z or o (corresponding
%                           to x) or e (corresponding to y)
%                       - temperature : Temperature when the temperature 
%                           dependence is in the database (in K)
%                       - pressure : Pressure of air (in Pa)
%                       - humidity : Relative humidity of air (0 to 1)
%                       - CO2 : CO2 concentration in air (in ppm)
%                       - deuteriumConcentration : Concentration of
%                           deuterium in DKDP (55%, 70% and 80% only)
%                       - displayWarnings : If one of the additional
%                           parameters is wrong, the code will display a
%                           warning message. In order not to display it,
%                           just enter false
%                       - allowSellmeierOutsideBoundaries : Boolean to
%                           allow you to get some data without checking the
%                           validity range of the Sellmeier equation used.
%                           This should in principle always stay at "false"
%                           level, except for very special cases (I
%                           implemented it for nitrogen in the MIR)
%                       - needForSpeed : Boolean which allows to disable
%                           the evaluation of the multiple derivatives 
%
% Output parameters : The output is a cell containing 2 fiels. The first
%                       one is an array with the refractive index requested
%                       (or an array of those in case the input wavelength
%                       is an array) and the second one (not mandatory) is
%                       is a structure containing as many data about the
%                       material as possible. Most materials have at least
%                       the following fields :
%                       - input_xxx : copy of all the input parameters
%                       - n_function : When a Sellmeier equation is
%                           available, it returns a function handle that
%                           one can evaluate as
%                           output_struct.n_function(lambda)
%                         - lambda_min : Smallest wavelength of refractive
%                           index measurement in the source article
%                         - lambda_max : Biggest wavelength of refractive
%                           index measurement in the source article
%                         - birefringence : birefringence of material (not
%                           birefringent, uniaxial, biaxial)
%                         - axis : Axis considered. For non-birefringent
%                           crystals, x = o. For uniaxial crystals, x = o
%                           and y = e.
%                         - source_n : Source of the refractive index. Most
%                           of the time, it's just the DOI, but sometimes
%                           it's a link to the website of the conference
%                           where it was published (no DOI)
%                         - source_n2 : Source for the non linear
%                           refractive index
%
% Required codes : None (except if you use copy paste the example of use
%   below, and in that case, you need some functions which are in 
%   hhs/OPCPA-E4/codes/functions/functions_PAC)
%
% Remarks : Since for most materials, different papers cover different
%   wavelength ranges, the code will automatically  pick-up the right
%   equation for the input wavelength. In case of overlap between two
%   equations, I take the one which looks the most "trustable" as a
%   reference (either the latest one, either the most cited one), except
%   for MgO:PPLN in which I use the reference publication of HCP Photonics.
%   Since in the case of the mid-IR OPCPA, the temperature dependance is
%   most of the time of primary importance, I didn't insert it in this
%   code. Still, some of the publications I've used provide the temperature
%   dependance. So if it is of interest for you, check directly on the
%   publication.
%
% Example of use :
%     wavelength_list = 1000e-9 : 1e-9 : 1500e-9;
%     ne_MgOCLN       = getRefractiveIndex('MgOCLN' , wavelength_list, ...
%                                          'axis' , 'e', ...
%                                          'temperature' , 293);
%     plot(wavelength_list * 1e9 , ne_MgOCLN)
%     xlabel('Wavelength (nm)')
%     ylabel('Refractive index')
%     title(['Refractive index of Magnesium Oxyde doped Congruent' , ...
%            'Lithium Niobate along the extraordinary axis'])
%     grid on
%     makeItNice
%     [n_value , output_struct] = getRefractiveIndex('MgOCLN' , wavelength_list, ...
%                                                    'axis' , 'e', ...
%                                                    'temperature' , 293);
%     disp2(['For MgOCLN along the extraordinary axis, the Sellmeier ' , ...
%           'equation existing starts at ' , ...
%           num2str(output_struct.lambda_min * 1e9) , ...
%           ' nm and ends at ' , ...
%           num2str(output_struct.lambda_max * 1e9) , ...
%           ' nm. Reference publication DOI is ' , ...
%           output_struct.source])
%
% If you want to add a material and being able to compute its dispersion
% coefficients (GD, GDD, TOD ...) as a function_handle, you need to have
% the symbolic computing toolbox installed and execute the following :
%     syms x; % Symbolic x
%     A1  = 4.07205767;
%     B1  = 2.08841706e-1;
%     A2  = 7.44196974e-1;
%     B2  = 3.95964740e-1;
%     A3  = 9.88377784e-1;
%     B3  = 2.77481958e1;
%     output_struct.n_function    = @(lambda) sqrt(1 + ...
%                                                A1 .* (lambda*10^6).^2 ./ ((lambda*10^6).^2 - B1^2) + ...
%                                                A2 .* (lambda*10^6).^2 ./ ((lambda*10^6).^2 - B2^2) + ...
%                                                A3 .* (lambda*10^6).^2 ./ ((lambda*10^6).^2 - B3^2));
%     dn_over_dlambda     = matlabFunction(diff(output_struct.n_function(x)))
%     d2n_over_dlambda2   = matlabFunction(diff(diff(output_struct.n_function(x))))
%     d3n_over_dlambda3   = matlabFunction(diff(diff(diff(output_struct.n_function(x)))))
%     d4n_over_dlambda4   = matlabFunction(diff(diff(diff(diff(output_struct.n_function(x))))))
%     d5n_over_dlambda5   = matlabFunction(diff(diff(diff(diff(diff(output_struct.n_function(x)))))))
%     output_struct.dn_over_dlambda   = ;
%     output_struct.d2n_over_dlambda2 = ;
%     output_struct.d3n_over_dlambda3 = ;
%     output_struct.d4n_over_dlambda4 = ;
%     output_struct.d5n_over_dlambda5 = ;
% You can then make a copy paste of the derivatives found, and you won't
% have to redo the symbolic calculation of the derivatives everytime
% you execute the code.
%
% List of modifications :
%   - v1.0 : Implementation of the code, check of all the materials (except
%            air in the mid-IR), removal of the GVD calculation, finishing
%            the documentation
%   - v1.1 : Implementation of the calculation of the multiple derivatives
%            of the refractive index when a Sellmeier equation exists with
%            the help of the symbolic differentials (please note two
%            exceptions :
%            - air : because of the huge number of parameters, getting
%            fixed derivative is impossible, so I didn't implement anything
%            for this yet, but a live calculation of the derivatives with
%            the symbolic toolbox is feasible
%            - Lithium Niobate : in the Sellmeier I've chosen for it (same
%            as HCP Photonics), there is temperature dependance. In order
%            not to make it too complex, I've fixed the temperature for the
%            calculation of the derivatives at 24C (temperature in E4).
%            The Sellmeier equation is still dependant on temperature.
%   - v1.2 : Added the nonlinear refractive index n2 for multiple
%            materials (BaF2, BBO, CaCO3, CdTe, KBr, LiF, MgF2, MgOCLN,
%            NaCl ,Sapphire, UVFS, ZnS, ZnSe, ZnTe) and corrected the n2
%            of air (which was off by a factor of 10^23 in v1.1). Also
%            added a few new materials (CaCO3, CdTe, KBr, LiF, MgF2, NaCl,
%            ZnTe)
%   - v1.3 : Added calculation of dispersion for air between 230 nm and
%            1.69 um for 2 cases. In the case of standard air, I
%            precomputed the dn/dlambda formulas to go faster. The second
%            case is if other parameters than standard air are provided
%            (humidity, temperature, or CO2 concentration). In that case,
%            the code makes a symbolic calculation of the dispersion
%            relations, which takes around 300 ms and gives the result of
%            the dispersion parameters in the standard format in the
%            output_struct.
%   - v1.4 : Added quartz (0.18-3.0 um) for waveplate retardation calc.
%   - v1.5 : Added nitrogen between 0.4679 and 2.05 um and the possibility
%            to use a Sellmeier formula even one is not supposed to use it
%            (not in the right boundaries)
%   - v1.6 : Added the option 'needForSpeed' to go faster by bypassing the
%           computation of the multiple derivatives of the refractive index
%   - v1.7 : Added the axis available in the output_struct.
%   - v1.8 : Added n2 of N.
%   - v1.9 : Added n2 of Quartz.
%   - v1.10: Added n of BiBO and changed the n source of LBO to Kato (to
%            match SNLO calculations), and added LiIO3, KTA and KNbO3
%   - v1.11: Added n of MgOCLN from another publication (x axis in the
%            full range of the Sellmeier) : Zelmon, I called it MgOCLN_2.
%            I also added the temperature dependance of MgOCLN in
%            n_function. Also added YCOB.
%   - v1.12: Added d_eff of multiple materials (YCOB, KNbO3, BBO, BiBo, 
%            MgOCLN, MgOCLN_2)
%   - v1.13: Added refractive indices for all noble gases (except Radon)
%               and their nonlinear refractive indices (wavelength
%               dependence computed from Keldysh theory)
%   - v1.14: Added Suprasil
%
% Last modification : 22.07.2021
%
% Author : Pierre-Alexis Chevreuil (chpierre@phys.ethz.ch)

%% Setting default values and checking inputs through a parser
defaultAxis                                 = 'x'; % x, y, z, o or e
defaultTemperature                          = 293; % Kelvin
defaultPressure                             = 101325; % Pa
defaultHumidity                             = 0.4; % 0 to 1
defaultCO2                                  = 450; % ppm
defaultdisplayWarnings                      = true; % Displays some warnings in the command window in case something goes wrong
defaultLengthLineWarningsNum                = 60;
defaultDeuteriumConcentration               = 0.55;
defaultAllowingSellmeierOutsideBoundaries   = false;
defaultNeedForSpeed                         = false;            

expectedAxis                    = {'x','y','z','o','e'};
deuteriumConcentrationPossible  = [0.55 0.70 0.80];

p                   = inputParser; % Creates the parser
validScalarPosNum   = @(x) isnumeric(x) && isscalar(x) && (x >= 0); % Function to test the input parameters, just for robustness
validScalar0To1     = @(x) isnumeric(x) && isscalar(x) && (x >= 0) && (x <= 1); % Function to test the input parameters, just for robustness

addRequired(    p,  'material',                         @ischar);
addRequired(    p,  'lambda',                           @isvector);

addParameter(   p,  'displayWarnings',                  defaultdisplayWarnings,                     @islogical);
addParameter(   p,  'axis',                             defaultAxis,                                @(x) any(validatestring(x,expectedAxis)));
addParameter(   p,  'temperature',                      defaultTemperature,                         validScalarPosNum);
addParameter(   p,  'pressure',                         defaultPressure,                            validScalarPosNum);
addParameter(   p,  'humidity',                         defaultHumidity,                            validScalar0To1);
addParameter(   p,  'CO2',                              defaultCO2,                                 validScalarPosNum);
addParameter(   p,  'lengthLineWarningNum',             defaultLengthLineWarningsNum,               validScalarPosNum);
addParameter(   p,  'deuteriumConcentration',           defaultDeuteriumConcentration,              @(x) ismember(x,deuteriumConcentrationPossible));
addParameter(   p,  'allowSellmeierOutsideBoundaries',  defaultAllowingSellmeierOutsideBoundaries,  @islogical);
addParameter(   p,  'needForSpeed',                     defaultNeedForSpeed,                        @islogical);

parse(p, material, lambda, varargin{:});
saveParse = p.Results;

displayWarnings                     = p.Results.displayWarnings;
axis                                = p.Results.axis; % Puts either the data entered at the beginning
temperature                         = p.Results.temperature; % in the variable, either it takes the
pressure                            = p.Results.pressure; % default values
humidity                            = p.Results.humidity;
CO2                                 = p.Results.CO2;
lengthLineWarningNum                = p.Results.lengthLineWarningNum;
lengthLineWarningText               = ['.{',num2str(lengthLineWarningNum),',',num2str(lengthLineWarningNum),'}\s'];
deuteriumConcentration              = p.Results.deuteriumConcentration;
allowSellmeierOutsideBoundaries     = p.Results.allowSellmeierOutsideBoundaries;
needForSpeed                        = p.Results.needForSpeed;

%% Initialization
c                               = 299792458;
N_a                             = 6.02214086e23; % Avogadro
output_struct                   = struct;
outsideOfSellmeierRange         = false; % Assumes that everything is fine, this variable will be changed only if something goes wrong
zeroToAllFields                 = false; % Assumes that everything is fine, this variable will be changed only if something goes wrong
temperatureWrong                = false; % Assumes that everything is fine, this variable will be changed only if something goes wrong
pressureWrong                   = false; % Assumes that everything is fine, this variable will be changed only if something goes wrong
humidityWrong                   = false; % Assumes that everything is fine, this variable will be changed only if something goes wrong
CO2wrong                        = false; % Assumes that everything is fine, this variable will be changed only if something goes wrong
oneOptionalParameterWrong       = false; % Assumes that everything is fine, this variable will be changed only if something goes wrong
wrongAxis                       = false; % Assumes that everything is fine, this variable will be changed only if something goes wrong
materialExisting                = true; % Assumes that everything is fine, this variable will be changed only if something goes wrong
noTemperatureDependance         = true; % Assumes that everything is fine, this variable will be changed only if something goes wrong (mandatory for MgOCLN because of temperature dependance, it's impossible to compute the analytic derivatives of n)

if strcmp(axis, 'o') % x = ordinary for uniaxial and biaxial crystals if we consider nx < ny < nz and no < ne
    axis = 'x';
elseif strcmp(axis, 'e') % y = extraordinary for uniaxial and biaxial crystals if we consider nx < ny < nz and no < ne
    axis = 'y';
end

if allowSellmeierOutsideBoundaries
    displayWarnings = false;
end

%% Beginning of the code
switch material
    case 'air' % Checked for the first Sellmeier, not in the mid-IR
        output_struct.axis_available = {'x'};
        wavelength_range = Inf; % For the visible range, fully checked for temperature, humidity and pressure (CO2 fixed, lambda fixed, checked with table 3 of the article)
        if (((min(lambda) >= 0.23e-6) && (max(lambda) <= 1.69e-6) && ... % Checked
            (temperature >= 233) && (temperature <= 373) && ... % Checked
            (pressure >= 80000) && (pressure <= 120000) && ... % Checked
            (humidity >= 0) && (humidity <= 1) && ... % Checked
            (CO2 >= 0) && (CO2 <= 650)) || allowSellmeierOutsideBoundaries) % Not very well specified in the paper, I took those numbers since some data exist
            a0      = 1.58123e-6; % K.Pa^(-1)
            a1      = -2.9331e-8; % Pa^(-1)
            a2      = 1.1043e-10; % K^-1.Pa^(-1)
            b0      = 5.707e-6; % K.Pa^(-1)
            b1      = -2.051e-8; % Pa^(-1)
            c0      = 1.9898e-4; % K.Pa^(-1)
            c1      = -2.376e-6; % Pa^(-1)
            d       = 1.83e-11; % K^2.Pa^(-2)
            e       = -0.765e-8; % K^2.Pa^(-2)
            k0      = 238.0185; % um^(-2)
            k1      = 5792105; % um^(-2)
            k2      = 57.362; % um^(-2)
            k3      = 167917; % um^(-2)
            w0      = 295.235; % um^(-4)
            w1      = 2.6422; % um^(-4)
            w2      = -0.032380; % um^(-4)
            w3      = 0.004028; % um^(-4)
            R       = 8.314510; % Gas constant, J.mol^(-1).K^(-1) (the value is not a mistake : 
                                % the value has been corrected since the publication of the article,
                                % but I prefered using the value given in the article)
            A       = 1.2378847e-5; % K^(-2)
            B       = -1.9121316e-2; % K^(-1)
            C       = 33.93711047; % unitless
            D       = -6.3431645e3; % K
            alpha   = 1.00062; % unitless
            beta    = 3.14e-8; % Pa^(-1)
            gamma   = 5.6e-7; % C^(-2)
            Mw      = 0.018015; % Molar mass of water vapor in kg.mol^(-1)
            xc      = CO2; % Notation of the article
            Z       = @(temperature, pressure, xw)      1 - (pressure./temperature) .* ...
                                                        (a0 + a1*(temperature - 273.15) + ...
                                                        a2*(temperature - 273.15).^2 + ...
                                                        (b0 + b1*(temperature - 273.15)) .* ...
                                                        xw + (c0 + c1*(temperature - 273.15)) .* ...
                                                        xw.^2) + (pressure./temperature).^2 .* ...
                                                        (d + e*xw.^2); % Compressibility
            sigma   = @(lambda)                         1./(lambda*1e6); % Wavenumber in um^(-1)
            if (temperature >= 273.15)
                svp = exp(A*temperature.^2 + B*temperature + C + D./temperature); % Saturation vapor pressure of water vapor in air
            else
                svp = 10.^(-2663.5./temperature + 12.537); % Vapor pressure over ice (very small, should lead to f close to 1)
            end
            f       = alpha + beta.*pressure + gamma.*(temperature - 273.15).^2; % Enhancement factor of water vapor in air
            xw      = f .* humidity .* svp ./ pressure; % Molar fraction of water vapor in moist air
            nas     = @(lambda) 1 + 1e-8 * (k1 ./ (k0 - sigma(lambda).^2) + k3 ./ (k2 - sigma(lambda).^2) ); % Refractive index of standard air at 15 C,
                                                                                                             % 101325 Pa, 0% humidity, 450 ppm CO2
            naxs    = @(lambda) 1 + (nas(lambda) - 1) * (1 + 0.534e-6 * (xc - 450)); % Refractive index of standard air at 15 �C, 101325 Pa, 0% humidity, xc ppm CO2
            nws     = @(lambda) 1 + 1.022 * 1e-8 * (w0 + w1*sigma(lambda).^2 + ...
                                w2*sigma(lambda).^4 + w3*sigma(lambda).^6); % Refractive index of water vapor at standard conditions (20 �C, 1333 Pa)
            Ma      = 1e-3 * (28.9635 + 12.011e-6 * (xc - 400)); % Molar mass of dry air in kg.mol^(-1)
            Za      = Z(288.15, 101325, 0); % Compressibility of dry air
            Zw      = Z(293.15, 1333,   1); % Compressibility of pure water vapor
            rho_axs = 101325 .* Ma ./ (Za * R * 288.15); % Density of standard air (equation 4 with (temperature = 288.15 K, pressure = 1333 Pa and xw = 0)
            rho_ws  = 1333 * Mw ./ (Zw * R * 293.15); % Density of standard water vapor (equation 4 with temperature = 293.15 K, pressure = 1333 Pa and xw = 1)
            rho_a   = pressure .* Ma ./ (Z(temperature, pressure, xw) * R .* temperature) * (1 - xw); % Density of the dry component of moist air
            rho_w   = pressure .* Mw ./ (Z(temperature, pressure, xw) * R .* temperature) .* xw; % Density of the water vapor component of moist air
            
            output_struct.temperature_min   = 233;
            output_struct.temperature_max   = 373;
            output_struct.pressure_min      = 80000;
            output_struct.pressure_max      = 120000;
            output_struct.humidity_min      = 0;
            output_struct.humidity_max      = 1;
            output_struct.CO2_min           = 0;
            output_struct.CO2_max           = 2000;
            output_struct.name              = 'air';
            output_struct.birefringence     = 'not birefringent';
            output_struct.axis              = 'none';
            output_struct.n_function        = @(lambda) 1 + (rho_a ./ rho_axs) .* (naxs(lambda) - 1) + (rho_w ./ rho_ws) .* (nws(lambda) - 1);
            output_struct.n_value           = output_struct.n_function(lambda);
            output_struct.lambda_min        = 0.23e-6;
            output_struct.lambda_max        = 1.69e-6;
            output_struct.source_n          = '10.1364/AO.35.001566';
            wavelength_range = 0;
            
            if (temperature == defaultTemperature) && ...
                    (pressure == defaultPressure) && ...
                    (humidity == defaultHumidity) && ...
                    (CO2 == defaultCO2)% If we are in standard air config, I use precomputed values of derivatives of Sellmeier to save time
                output_struct.dn_over_dlambda   = @(x)  1.0./x.^3.*1.0./(1.0./x.^2./1.0e+12-5.7362e+1).^2.*(-3.272319841478553e-15)-1.0./x.^3.*1.0./(1.0./x.^2./1.0e+12-2.380185e+2).^2.*1.128749329456049e-13-1.0./x.^3.*3.77153191185188e-20+1.0./x.^5.*9.243978752990983e-34-1.0./x.^7.*1.724895603013327e-46;
                output_struct.d2n_over_dlambda2 = @(x)  1.0./x.^4.*1.0./(1.0./x.^2./1.0e+12-5.7362e+1).^2.*9.81695952443566e-15-1.0./x.^6.*1.0./(1.0./x.^2./1.0e+12-5.7362e+1).^3.*1.308927936591421e-26+1.0./x.^4.*1.0./(1.0./x.^2./1.0e+12-2.380185e+2).^2.*3.386247988368147e-13-1.0./x.^6.*1.0./(1.0./x.^2./1.0e+12-2.380185e+2).^3.*4.514997317824196e-25+1.0./x.^4.*1.131459573555564e-19-1.0./x.^6.*4.621989376495492e-33+1.0./x.^8.*1.207426922109329e-45;
                output_struct.d3n_over_dlambda3 = @(x)  1.0./x.^5.*1.0./(1.0./x.^2./1.0e+12-5.7362e+1).^2.*(-3.926783809774264e-14)+1.0./x.^7.*1.0./(1.0./x.^2./1.0e+12-5.7362e+1).^3.*1.178035142932279e-25-1.0./x.^9.*1.0./(1.0./x.^2./1.0e+12-5.7362e+1).^4.*7.853567619548528e-38-1.0./x.^5.*1.0./(1.0./x.^2./1.0e+12-2.380185e+2).^2.*1.354499195347259e-12+1.0./x.^7.*1.0./(1.0./x.^2./1.0e+12-2.380185e+2).^3.*4.063497586041776e-24-1.0./x.^9.*1.0./(1.0./x.^2./1.0e+12-2.380185e+2).^4.*2.708998390694517e-36-1.0./x.^5.*4.525838294222256e-19+1.0./x.^7.*2.773193625897295e-32-1.0./x.^9.*9.659415376874631e-45;
